# SIDE QUEST — "The Forty-One"  (requires sq.reaper_hidden_souls)
# The Last Honest Psychopomp hid forty-one fading Faithless souls instead of delivering them to the Wall —
# kept them in the folds of his cloak, ten thousand years, slowing their fading by sheer refusal. Now they
# are nearly gone, and he cannot hide them much longer. What becomes of the forty-one the reaper saved?
class: FugueSideQuestContent

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# "The Forty-One" — the souls the reaper hid; where they finally go.
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
conversation: sq.fugue.fortyone | The Forty-One
node: 0 | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper waits at the edge of the grey, and his cloak — you understand now — is not empty. It moves with a faint inner light, forty-one small fading glimmers held in its folds, sheltered from the Wall's pull by the body of the one psychopomp who refused to deliver them. He holds the cloak close, like a man holding the last warmth of a fire.)* You came back. *(quietly.)* I half-hoped you wouldn't. It would mean the *choice* stayed mine, and a choice you keep alone is at least one you can't *fail* someone else with. *(he opens the cloak a little; the glimmers flutter, weak.)* Forty-one. That's all that's left. I've hidden them ten thousand years — slowed their fading by *standing between them and the Wall* with my own body. *(he meets your eyes.)* But I'm only a reaper, not a god. They're nearly *out.* And I cannot hide them another age. I've kept them alive long enough to reach *you.* Now you have to help me decide where the forty-one finally *go.*
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_begun
  auto: 1
node: 1 | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(He cradles the cloak, and the forty-one glimmers pulse faintly within.)* Let me tell you who they are, so you choose with their faces and not a number. *(quietly.)* This one — *(a glimmer)* — was a midwife who doubted the gods the night a mother died under her hands. This one, a boy who asked the wrong question in temple and never got to take it back. This one *(another)* loved someone the gods forbade and chose the love. *(his voice tightens.)* Forty-one souls the Wall marked *faithless* — and I, whose *whole office* is to *deliver* the dead to their sorting, *looked* at them, *one by one*, over ten thousand years, and *could not do it.* So I *hid* them. *Stole* them, by the doctrine. *(he meets your eyes.)* And now they're *fading* anyway — slower, because I *held* them, but *fading* — and I have to choose between three things, none of which I can bear alone: let them *finish fading*, gently, in my keeping. Try to get them *out* — to the graves, to rest, to *somewhere.* Or — *(his voice drops)* — the thing I've never dared, that might *save* them or might *scatter* them: *let them go into the un-kept.* The fall. The thing the gardener wept for. *(he looks at you.)* I've hidden them ten thousand years. I don't know how to *stop.* Help me.
  * [INSIGHT 18] "You've kept them ten thousand years the way the Wall keeps everyone — slowing the fade, never letting them finish, holding them *between* states because letting go felt like failing them. Your hiding became its own gentle Wall, reaper. The forty-one don't need a better keeper. They need what you've been too afraid to give: an *ending.*" -> gentle_wall ?? guard
  * "There's a field beyond the Court — open graves, one for every soul the harvest took, kept by a coffin-man who waited ten thousand years to fill them. Your forty-one have *graves waiting*, reaper. Carry them there. Let the souls you hid be the first the field receives, with names and a place that was always theirs." -> graves | if act5.graves_waiting
  * "The Wall is breaking — names read free at the Court. Your forty-one don't have to *fade* and they don't have to *hide.* Carry them to the reading. Let each one be *named* aloud, *witnessed*, and then *released* whole — not lost into the un-kept, but freed the way the road has freed everyone: read, then let go." -> reading | if act5.wall_breaking
  * "You say you don't know how to stop hiding them. Then don't decide their ending by yourself — that's just the hiding in another shape, you alone holding their whole fate. Ask *them.* Open the cloak, and let the forty-one say what *they* want — to fade, to rest, to fall. They were never yours to keep. Only yours to *carry until they could choose.*" -> ask_them | fx appr.naeve +2
node: gentle_wall | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper goes very still, and the cloak trembles in his hands.)* ...My hiding became its own Wall. *(barely a whisper.)* No. *(then, quieter:)* ...Yes. *(he looks down at the forty-one fading glimmers.)* I have *despised* the Wall for ten thousand years — the *keeping*, the *holding*, the *never-letting-finish* — and I have done the *exact* same thing, *here*, in my *own* cloak, and called it *mercy* because I did it with *love* instead of *doctrine.* *(his voice breaks.)* But the *gardener* taught you, and you've taught *me*: *kinder keeping is still keeping.* I *slowed* their fading. I did not *let* them *complete.* I held them *between* — not walled, not freed, not fallen, just — *held*, by *me*, because *letting go* felt like *losing* them and I am a *reaper* who could not bear to *lose* the *only* souls I ever *saved.* *(he meets your eyes.)* They're not *mine.* I made them *mine* by *holding* them, the way the *Wall* makes the *Faithless* *its* by *keeping* them. *(he draws a shaking breath.)* You're right. The forty-one don't need a *better keeper.* They need the *thing* I was *too afraid* to give — the *ending* I *stole* from them by *saving* them. *(quietly.)* Help me *stop* hiding. Help me give them the *fall* I've *denied* them for ten thousand years out of *love.* It's *time.* I've held them long enough. *Past* long enough. *Let* me learn to *let* go.
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_gentle_wall, SET act4.deathless_is_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: 2
node: graves | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper's head comes up sharply, and hope — a thing he has not let himself feel in an age — breaks across his face.)* Graves. *Waiting.* *(he clutches the cloak.)* You mean — there's a *place.* An *actual* *place*, with *holes* already *dug*, *names* already *set*, for souls the *harvest* *took.* *(his voice fills.)* I have hidden the forty-one ten thousand years with *nowhere* to *put* them — that was the *whole* *agony*, I could *save* them from the *Wall* but I had *nowhere* to *take* them, so I just — *held* them, *endlessly*, because *letting go* meant letting them *fall into nothing.* *(he meets your eyes.)* But a *grave* — a *grave* is not *nothing.* A grave is *rest.* A *named* place. A *fitting* end. *(the forty-one glimmers pulse, as if they hear.)* Carry them to the field. *Yes.* Let the *coffin-man* who waited ten thousand years to *fill* his graves and *me*, who waited ten thousand years to *set down* my forty-one — let us *meet* at the *field*, and *bury* them *together*, *named*, *resting*, *first* of all the souls that field receives. *(his voice breaks with relief.)* I didn't *fail* them by hiding them. I *kept* them *safe* until there was *somewhere* worth *taking* them. *(he meets your eyes.)* The graves are the *somewhere.* Lead me there. *Forty-one* souls, *hidden* an *age*, finally going *home* to a *hole* that *fits* and a *stone* that *names* them. *Let's* take them *home.*
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_to_the_graves, SET act5.graves_being_filled, SET act5.graves_waiting, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: 2
node: reading | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper listens, and something in his weary frame straightens with dawning purpose.)* The Wall is breaking. Names read free. *(slowly.)* And my forty-one don't have to *fade* — and don't have to *hide.* *(he opens the cloak; the glimmers flutter toward the light.)* I have kept them *secret* ten thousand years — *unnamed*, *unspoken*, *hidden* even from *each other*, because to *speak* a hidden soul's name was to *risk* the Wall *hearing* it and *claiming* it. *(his voice fills.)* But if the Wall is *breaking* — if names are being *read free* instead of *filed* — then the *one* thing I could *never* do becomes the *one* thing that *saves* them: *say their names. Out loud. Witnessed.* *(he meets your eyes.)* Carry them to the *reading.* Let each of the forty-one be *named* — the *midwife*, the *boy*, the *one who loved* — *witnessed*, *known*, *real*, and *then* *released* whole, the way you've freed *everyone* down this road. *Not* faded into *nothing* in my cloak. *Not* fallen *unnamed* into the un-kept. *Read.* *Then* let go. *(the glimmers pulse brighter, as if they understand.)* I hid them because *naming* them meant *losing* them to the Wall. *(quietly, wondering.)* And now *naming* them is how they get *free.* *(he meets your eyes.)* Ten thousand years of *silence*, and the *ending* is to finally *say* their *names.* Take us to the reading. *All* forty-one. *Let* them be *spoken.*
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_to_the_reading, SET act5.wall_breaking, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: 2
node: ask_them | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper freezes — and then a look of profound, shamed recognition crosses his face.)* ...Ask them. *(quietly.)* In ten thousand years, I have *never* — *(he looks down at the cloak.)* I *saved* them. I *hid* them. I *carried* them. I have made *every* decision *for* them — to *take* them, to *hold* them, to *slow* their *fading* — and *not* *once*, in *all* that time, have I *asked* a *single* one of them what *they* *wanted.* *(his voice breaks.)* Because I was *afraid* of the *answer.* Afraid one of them would say *"let me finish, reaper, I'm tired"* — and that I'd have to *honor* it, and *lose* them, and I *couldn't* *bear* it. *(he meets your eyes.)* So I kept them *silent.* *Decided* for them. *Exactly* like the Wall, which *never* asks the Faithless if they'd *rather* be *nothing* than *kept.* *(he draws a shaking breath, and slowly, slowly, opens the cloak wide.)* You're right. They were *never* mine to *keep.* Only mine to *carry* — until they could *choose.* *(the forty-one glimmers drift up, into the open air, free of the folds for the first time in an age, and they *brighten*, and a sound comes from them — small, layered, like forty-one voices remembering they have voices.)* *(the reaper weeps.)* Speak, then. *All* of you. I've *held* you *silent* ten thousand years because I was *afraid* to *hear* you *choose.* *(quietly, to you:)* Help me *listen.* Whatever they *want* — to *fade*, to *rest*, to *fall* — I will *honor* it, *finally*, instead of *deciding* it. *Forty-one* *choices.* Not *one* reaper's *fear.* *That's* the *ending* they're *owed.*
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_ask_them, SET act5.witness_then_release, SET act3.break_the_crown_known, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +6
  auto: 2
node: 2 | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper holds the cloak — lighter now, or perhaps only held differently — the forty-one glimmers within it pulsing toward whatever ending you've helped him reach. He looks at you, ten thousand years of solitary keeping finally near its close.)* Whatever happens now, *(quietly)* I want you to know — they were *worth* it. The *hiding.* The *ten thousand years* of *standing between* them and the *Wall.* Even if it was its *own* kind of keeping, even if I held too long — they were *worth* *refusing* the *doctrine* for. *(he meets your eyes.)* The *other* psychopomps *delivered* their dead to the *sorting*, *clean*, *obedient*, *guiltless.* I *stole* forty-one and *carried* them an *age* and it *cost* me *everything* — my *office*, my *peace*, my *certainty* — and I would do it *again.* *(quietly.)* What do I do, after? When the forty-one are finally *gone* — *rested*, *freed*, *whatever* we *choose* — and my *cloak* is *empty* for the *first* time in ten thousand years?
  * "You join the line. There's an unbroken chain of souls who do the eternal work — grave-tenders, list-keepers, the ones who refuse to let the forgotten go untended. You're one of them, reaper. The first psychopomp who refused. When your cloak's empty, go find the *next* forty-one. There are always more the Wall is taking." -> line | fx SET sq.fortyone_reaper_joins_line, SET act5.unbroken_line, appr.garrow +4
  * "You rest, reaper. You've carried forty-one souls for ten thousand years — you've earned an ending too. When the cloak's empty, lie down in the graves field beside the ones you saved. The keeper of the forty-one deserves a grave that fits, same as them." -> rest | fx SET sq.fortyone_reaper_rests, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  * "You let the empty cloak be a *victory*, not a loss. For ten thousand years it was heavy because you were *failing* to save them — holding them between, unable to finish. An empty cloak means you *succeeded*: they're *free*, or *rested*, or *home.* Carry the emptiness proudly. It's the shape of forty-one endings you finally allowed." -> victory | fx appr.naeve +4
node: line | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper considers it, and slowly his weary face settles into something like resolve.)* Join the line. *(quietly.)* The *unbroken* one. *(he looks toward the grey, where the Wall still takes its daily harvest.)* You're right that it doesn't *stop.* Even with the Wall *breaking*, even with *these* forty-one *freed* — there are *more*, *always* more, souls the machine is *taking* *right now*, *fading* *unhidden* because there's *no* reaper *standing* *between* them and the *sorting.* *(he meets your eyes.)* I was the *first* psychopomp to *refuse.* I thought that made me a *criminal*, a *thief*, an *aberration.* *(his voice firms.)* But you've shown me the *line* — the *grave-tenders*, the *list-keepers*, the *coffin-man*, all the *strangers* in *every* era who *pick up the work* of *refusing* to let the *forgotten* *go untended.* *(he draws the empty-growing cloak around him.)* I'm *one* of them. The *reaper* who *refused.* *(quietly, with purpose.)* So when these forty-one are *home* — *rested*, *freed* — I *won't* *stop.* I'll go *back* to the *grey*, to the *sorting*, and I'll *stand* *between* the *Wall* and the *next* fading soul, and the *next*, and *hide* *another* *forty-one*, and *another*, for as *long* as the *machine* keeps *taking.* *(he meets your eyes.)* The cloak won't *stay* empty. It was *never* *meant* to. *That's* the *work.* *That's* the *line.* And now I know I'm *in* it — not *alone*, not an *aberration*, but *one* more *hand* that *refused.* *Thank* you. An *empty* cloak isn't an *ending* for me. It's a *between-ferries.* There are *always* more to *carry.*
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_reaper_joins_line, SET act5.unbroken_line, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.garrow +5
  auto: close
node: rest | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper's weary eyes fill, and the cloak — forty-one glimmers lighter now in the imagining — seems to ease on his shoulders.)* Rest. *(barely above a whisper.)* *Me.* *(he looks at you as though the idea is a foreign language.)* In ten thousand years, no one has ever — *(his voice catches.)* I am the one who *carries* the *resting* to *others.* The *ferryman* of *endings.* It never — it *never* occurred to me that the *ferryman* might *also* be *owed* a *shore.* *(he draws a shaking breath.)* I have *stood* at the *edge* of the *grey* for *ten thousand years*, *hiding* forty-one souls, *unable* to *put* them *down* and *unable* to *put* *myself* *down*, because a *reaper* who *rests* is a reaper who *stops*, and *stopping* meant *abandoning* them. *(he meets your eyes.)* But if they're *home* — *rested*, *freed*, in *graves* that *fit* — then I have *nothing* left to *hold*, and for the *first* time in an *age*, I could — *(his voice breaks)* — I could *lie* *down.* *Beside* them. In the *field.* A *grave* for the *keeper* of the *forty-one*, *next* to the *forty-one* he *kept.* *(quietly, weeping, relieved.)* Yes. When the cloak is *empty* — I'll *rest.* I've *earned* it. *Ten thousand years* of *standing between* the *Wall* and the *fading*, and I never once *sat down.* *(he almost smiles.)* The *coffin-man* will dig me a *good* hole, I think. *Reaper-shaped.* *Right* beside the *souls* I *couldn't* let the *Wall* have. *(he meets your eyes.)* Thank you for *telling* me the *ferryman* gets a *shore* too. I *forgot.* I *forgot* I was *allowed* to *finish.*
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_reaper_rests, SET act4.deathless_is_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: close
node: victory | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The reaper looks down at his cloak — and slowly, as your words land, the way he holds it changes, from a clutch to something almost like an open hand.)* A victory. Not a loss. *(quietly.)* *(he turns the thought over.)* For ten thousand years, the *weight* of this cloak was the weight of *failure.* *(he meets your eyes.)* Every *day* it was *heavy* with forty-one souls I was *failing* to *truly* save — *holding* them, *yes*, but *between*, *unfinished*, *fading-slow* instead of *fading-fast*, a *worse* death dressed as a *rescue.* The *weight* was my *guilt.* *(his voice steadies.)* So when the cloak is *empty* — I've been *dreading* it as the *final* *failure*, the day I *lose* the *last* of them. *(slowly.)* But you're saying the *empty* cloak is the *opposite.* It's *proof* I *finally* *succeeded.* That the forty-one are *free*, or *rested*, or *home* — *finished*, the way the *gardener's* flower gets to *fall.* *(he draws the cloak around him, lighter.)* The *weight* was the *keeping.* The *emptiness* is the *letting-go.* *(he meets your eyes, and there's a hard-won peace in it.)* I'll carry the *empty* cloak *proudly.* Every *fold* that *used* to *hold* a *fading* soul now holds *nothing* — and *nothing*, for a soul that's *finally* *free*, is the *most* *beautiful* *weight* there is. *(quietly.)* Forty-one endings I *finally* allowed. *That's* what the emptiness *means.* Not *"I lost them."* *"I let them go."* *(he almost smiles.)* It only took me ten thousand years to learn the difference. *Thank* you for the *last* mile of it.
  enter: SET sq.fortyone_victory, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +4
  auto: close
node: guard | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(He draws the cloak protectively closed, the forty-one glimmers vanishing back into its folds.)* No. *(quietly, fiercely.)* Not yet. I *hear* you — *"keeping is keeping," "give them the ending"* — and *maybe* you're *right.* *(he holds the cloak close.)* But I have *carried* these forty-one for *ten thousand years*, and the thought of *opening* my *hands* — of *letting* them *fade* or *fall* or *finish* — it's — *(his voice shakes.)* They are the *only* thing I *saved.* The *only* good a *reaper* ever *did* against the *doctrine.* If I *let* them *go*, I'm — I'm just a *psychopomp* with an *empty* cloak again, and *everything* I *refused* for, *everything* it *cost* me, is — *(he stops.)* Not *yet.* Come back when I'm — when I can *bear* it. The forty-one have *faded* slowly for *ten thousand years.* They can *fade* a little *longer*, in my *keeping*, where they're *safe.* *(he turns away, holding the cloak, the reaper who saved forty-one souls and cannot yet save them from *himself* — but the glimmers within are fainter than when you came, and he knows it, and the knowing is in his eyes.)*
  auto: close
node: close | The Last Honest Psychopomp
  *(The Last Honest Psychopomp stands at the edge of the grey with his cloak of forty-one fading souls — the one reaper who refused the doctrine, who stole the Faithless he was meant to deliver and hid them an age against the Wall's pull — and whether you helped him carry them to the waiting graves, to the reading, to ask them their own ending, or recognized that his loving hiding had become its own gentle Wall, you carry away the ferryman's hard lesson, which is the whole road's: that even mercy can curdle into keeping, that the souls we love are never ours to hold but only ours to *carry until they can choose*, and that an empty cloak — ten thousand years in the making — is not the shape of a loss, but of forty-one endings finally, bravely, allowed.)*
